tasks.instruction:
1. Create a slash command configuration mapping in forge-web (e.g., lib/ai-context/slashCommandRouter.ts):
   /plan -> { skillName: 'plan', sessionType: 'plan', hint: 'User wants to create a task plan' }
   /next -> { skillName: 'next', sessionType: 'execute', hint: 'User wants to execute next task' }
   /discover -> { skillName: 'discover', sessionType: 'chat', hint: 'User wants to explore/discover' }
   /compound -> { skillName: 'compound', sessionType: 'compound', hint: 'User wants to extract lessons' }
   /decide -> { skillName: 'decide', sessionType: 'chat', hint: 'User wants to resolve decisions' }
   /objective -> { skillName: 'objective', sessionType: 'chat' }
   /idea -> { skillName: 'idea', sessionType: 'chat' }
   /status -> { skillName: null, sessionType: 'chat' }
   ... etc for all 20 commands
2. In ChatInput.tsx, when a slash command is detected and submitted:
   a. Look up the command in the router mapping.
   b. If skillName exists, auto-add it to skill_names in the sendMessage call.
   c. If sessionType exists, pass it as session_type.
   d. Pass the hint as additional context.
3. In chatStore.ts sendMessage(), accept and forward sessionType and initialHint.
4. Update SlashCommandDropdown to show skill-mapped commands with a workflow indicator.
5. Test: type /plan, verify skill is auto-attached and session_type is set.
